schools.name: Stanford University
schools.description: A leading research institution known for its entrepreneurial spirit and strong programs in engineering, business, and the sciences.

schools.name: Massachusetts Institute of Technology
schools.description: MIT in Cambridge, Massachusetts, is a global leader in science, engineering, and technology. The institute emphasizes hands-on learning and innovation, producing breakthroughs in fields ranging from artificial intelligence to renewable energy. MIT's entrepreneurial culture and research impact are central to its mission.

schools.name: Harvard University
schools.description: Harvard University in Cambridge, Massachusetts, is one of the most prestigious universities globally, recognized for its leadership in education, research, and innovation. With strengths across disciplines, Harvard's expansive resources, diverse student body, and influential alumni shape it into a hub for academic and professional achievement.

schools.name: Yale University
schools.description: Yale University, located in New Haven, Connecticut, is known for its academic excellence, historic campus, and vibrant community. The university offers a strong liberal arts curriculum alongside renowned professional programs in law, drama, and management. Yale's residential college system fosters close-knit communities and its alumni network includes leaders in politics, arts, and science.

schools.name: Princeton University
schools.description: Princeton University is known for its focus on undergraduate education, low student-to-faculty ratio, and excellence in fields like mathematics, physics, and public affairs. The campus's Collegiate Gothic architecture and generous financial aid contribute to its distinguished academic environment.

schools.name: University of Chicago
schools.description: The University of Chicago is renowned for its rigorous academic programs and influential research contributions. Located in Chicago's Hyde Park neighborhood, the university is known for its distinctive intellectual culture, the Chicago School of Economics, and its commitment to free inquiry and debate.

schools.name: Duke University
schools.description: Duke University in Durham, North Carolina, combines academic excellence with a vibrant campus life. Known for its strong programs in engineering, business, and medicine, Duke also boasts a successful athletic program and beautiful Gothic Revival architecture.

schools.name: Cornell University
schools.description: Cornell University, located in Ithaca, New York, is an Ivy League institution known for its diverse academic offerings and beautiful campus. From agriculture to engineering to veterinary medicine, Cornell provides world-class education across numerous disciplines.

schools.name: California Institute of Technology
schools.description: Caltech is a world-renowned science and engineering institute located in Pasadena, California. Despite its small size, Caltech has an outsized impact on scientific research and technological innovation, with numerous Nobel Prize winners among its faculty and alumni.

schools.name: Columbia University
schools.description: Columbia University, located in Manhattan, New York, is an Ivy League institution known for its journalism, business, and law programs. The university's urban campus provides students with unparalleled access to internships, cultural events, and networking opportunities.

schools.name: Northwestern University
schools.description: Northwestern University, located in Evanston, Illinois, is known for its strong programs in journalism, business, and engineering. The university's proximity to Chicago provides students with excellent internship and career opportunities.

schools.name: Johns Hopkins University
schools.description: Johns Hopkins University, located in Baltimore, Maryland, is a leading research university known for its medical school and public health programs. The university's commitment to research and innovation has made it a global leader in healthcare and scientific discovery.

schools.name: New York University
schools.description: NYU is a global university with campuses around the world, headquartered in New York City's Greenwich Village. Known for its strong programs in business, arts, and liberal arts, NYU offers students a truly international educational experience.

schools.name: University of Pennsylvania
schools.description: The University of Pennsylvania, located in Philadelphia, is an Ivy League institution known for its prestigious business school (Wharton) and strong programs across multiple disciplines. Penn's urban campus provides students with rich cultural and professional opportunities.

schools.name: University of Notre Dame
schools.description: The University of Notre Dame, located in Notre Dame, Indiana, is a Catholic research university known for its strong sense of community, excellent academics, and storied athletic programs. The university combines rigorous academics with a commitment to service and faith.

courses.name: Machine Learning
courses.description: Comprehensive introduction to machine learning algorithms including supervised learning, unsupervised learning, and reinforcement learning. Covers neural networks, support vector machines, and deep learning applications. Format combines theoretical lectures with programming assignments in Python/MATLAB. Prerequisites: Linear algebra, statistics, and programming experience.

courses.name: Artificial Intelligence
courses.description: Fundamental algorithms and data structures course covering sorting, searching, graph algorithms, and dynamic programming. Emphasizes both theoretical analysis and practical implementation. Format includes lectures, recitations, and challenging problem sets with programming components. Prerequisites: Programming experience and discrete mathematics.

courses.name: Justice: What's the Right Thing to Do?
courses.description: This legendary course explores fundamental questions of moral and political philosophy through contemporary case studies. Students engage with theories of justice from Aristotle to Rawls, examining ethical dilemmas in law, politics, and everyday life. Format includes large lectures with interactive discussions, small section meetings, and written assignments analyzing moral reasoning. No prerequisites required.

courses.name: The Psychology of Language
courses.description: An introduction to psycholinguistics examining how humans acquire, process, and use language. Topics include language development in children, the mental representation of words and grammar, language disorders, and the relationship between thought and language. Format combines lectures with laboratory exercises, including experiments on language processing. Prerequisites: Introduction to Psychology.

courses.name: Introduction to Psychology
courses.description: Comprehensive survey of psychological science covering perception, cognition, development, personality, and social psychology. Emphasizes scientific methodology and critical thinking about human behavior. Format includes engaging lectures, discussion sections, research participation opportunities, and multiple-choice and essay exams. No prerequisites.
